 modernity.’ The book provides a major intervention in the history of colonial medicine, as Hardiman argues that missionary medicine had a specific quality of its own – which he describes and analyses in detail – and that in most cases it was preferred to the medicine of colonial states. He also examines the period of transition to Indian independence, which was a highly fraught and uncertain process for the missionaries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBhil (Indic people)xHealth and hygienexHistoryy19th century. 0aBhil (Indic people)xHealth and hygienexHistoryy20th century. 0aBhil (Indic people)xMissionsxHistoryy19th century. 0aBhil (Indic people)xMissionsxHistoryy20th century. 0aMedicinexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aMissionszIndiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aMissionszIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMissions, MedicalzIndiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aMissions, MedicalzIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh  a1899 famine.  aAnglican mission.  aBhagats.  aBhil modernity.  aChristian healing.  aChurch Missionary Society.  aevangelism.  amission medicine.  apostcolonial era.  ashoe-string budget.  atribal India.  awoman's work.1 aHardiman, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611917940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526119179423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526119179/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles